Kenya recorded inflation rate of 3.73 per cent in April, the lowest in 60 months and marginally lower than 4.18 per cent recorded in March. Data by the Kenya National Bureau of Statistics shows in the period between March and April 2018, the food and non-alcoholic drinks index increased by 2.56 per cent to an average of 193.18 compared to 190.62 recorded a month before. â€œThis was mainly due to the increase in prices of some food stuffs which outweighed decreases recorded in respect to others. The year's inflation was however almost four times lower compared to 11.48 recorded in the corresponding month last year,'' KNBS This means, Kenyans dug dipper in pockets to purchase some items on the food basket. For instance, the cost of a kilogramme of onions recorded the largest increase; rising by almost Sh10 to Sh177.01 compared to Sh167.58 compared in March The price of kale - popularly known as sukuma wiki - also went up 5.5 per cent to retail at Sh56.10 up Sh53.06 per kilo the previous month. Maize flour prices eased during the month under review with two kilo packet of sifted maize flour going for Sh124.01 down from Sh124.51 while that of unpacked milk went down by few cents to retail at Sh60.82 from Sh61.17 The cost of housing, water, electricity, gas and other fuels increased by 3.24 per cent a move attributed to a slight price increase in the prices of house rent and cooking fuel. Charcoal prices went up significantly by 16.87 per cenT.